# Makefile toolchain preflight — every operator app, every target, every time

## The verbatim source (stated by Avery 2026-05-24)

> "this should have upon running the make file - a check shold be implemented for this and the put in place if not there for future runners on a new system and for any additioal upgrades we make to the app. its a rule."

Said immediately after `make ui` on this machine died with a cryptic message because the Rust toolchain wasn't installed yet:

```
failed to run 'cargo metadata' command to get workspace directory:
failed to run command cargo metadata --no-deps --format-version 1:
No such file or directory (os error 2)
```

A fresh-machine operator should never see that error. The Makefile knows it needs cargo — it should say so in plain English and point at the fix.

## The rule

Every `make` target in every operator app that depends on an external toolchain MUST:

1. **Declare its toolchain deps explicitly** via a `preflight-*` prerequisite target — `preflight-rust`, `preflight-python`, `preflight-node-pnpm`, `preflight-tauri`, `preflight-ios`, `preflight-launchctl`, etc.
2. **Hard-fail before the underlying tool runs** when a required toolchain is missing, with a chrome-block message naming the tool, why it's needed, and the **one-line install command**.
3. **Offer a scripted bootstrap** at `scripts/stack/bootstrap-<tool>.sh` for any toolchain that has a non-trivial install path (Rust). The bootstrap script is **opt-in** — preflight points at it; the operator runs it. When stdin is a TTY, preflight may prompt y/N to run it inline. **Never auto-mutate operator state without consent** (sister rule: [`contracts-and-prudence`](contracts-and-prudence.md)).
4. **Stay fast** — preflight on the happy path must add <100ms to every `make` invocation. No network calls, no version downloads, no GitHub queries. Pure `command -v` checks.
5. **Be cross-platform Mac + Linux**, with OS detection via `uname -s`. Mac-specific checks (Xcode CLT, launchctl) are gated by `Darwin`; Linux fallbacks (apt/dnf hints, systemctl) are gated by `Linux`. Windows is explicitly out of scope.

## When this fires

- Adding a new `make` target that shells out to a toolchain
- Adding a new toolchain dependency to an existing target (e.g. introducing Tauri to a previously pure-JS app)
- Bumping an existing toolchain's minimum version (`node >= 20` → `node >= 22`)
- Reviewing a PR that adds a Makefile target without a `preflight-*` prerequisite
- A fresh-machine bootstrap failed with a cryptic underlying-tool error — that's the smoke; this rule is the fire extinguisher

## When this does NOT fire

- `make` targets that only invoke other `make` targets (the inner target's preflight covers it)
- One-off helper scripts in `scripts/` that aren't wired into a `make` target (they get their own `command -v` checks if interactive, but no preflight wrapper)
- Repos with no `Makefile` at all (e.g. pure-docs repos like Historia in docs-only mode)

## The canonical pattern (already shipped in `automata`)

### Preflight script — `scripts/stack/preflight.sh`

One script, one positional arg per toolchain to check. Supported toolchain names:

| Name | Checks | Cross-platform |
|------|--------|----------------|
| `rust` | `cargo` + `rustc` on PATH | Mac + Linux |
| `python` | `python3` on PATH | Mac + Linux |
| `node-pnpm` | `node -v` >= 20 AND `pnpm` on PATH | Mac + Linux |
| `tauri` | `pnpm exec tauri --version` succeeds in `apps/pad-desktop` | Mac + Linux |
| `xcode-clt` | `xcode-select -p` succeeds (macOS only — silent pass on Linux) | Mac |
| `launchctl` | `launchctl` on macOS, `systemctl` on Linux | Mac + Linux |

Exit 0 on every-tool-present (silent, no stdout). Exit 1 on any miss, with a chrome block per missing tool plus an interactive y/N bootstrap prompt when stdin is a TTY.

### Bootstrap scripts — `scripts/stack/bootstrap-<tool>.sh`

- **`bootstrap-rust.sh`** — non-interactive `sh.rustup.rs -y --default-toolchain stable --profile minimal`. Native arm64 on Apple Silicon, native everything on Linux. Idempotent (exits 0 if cargo already present). Modifies `~/.zshenv`/`~/.profile` via rustup's own installer.
- **`bootstrap-python.sh`** — prints OS-appropriate install hint (`brew install python@3.12` on Darwin, `apt`/`dnf`/`pacman` on Linux). Does NOT auto-install — Python's install fragmentation makes auto-choosing surprising.

Other toolchains (node/pnpm, Xcode CLT, launchctl, Tauri CLI) get hints only — their install paths are too situational to safely script.

### Makefile wiring

```makefile
.PHONY: preflight preflight-rust preflight-python preflight-node-pnpm preflight-tauri preflight-ios preflight-launchctl

preflight-rust:      ; @bash scripts/stack/preflight.sh rust
preflight-python:    ; @bash scripts/stack/preflight.sh python
preflight-node-pnpm: ; @bash scripts/stack/preflight.sh node-pnpm
preflight-tauri:     preflight-node-pnpm ; @bash scripts/stack/preflight.sh tauri
preflight-ios:       preflight-rust       ; @bash scripts/stack/preflight.sh xcode-clt
preflight-launchctl: ; @bash scripts/stack/preflight.sh launchctl
preflight: preflight-node-pnpm preflight-python preflight-rust preflight-tauri
	@echo "✓ preflight passed."

# Targets declare their toolchain deps via the preflight prerequisites:
ui:              preflight-rust preflight-node-pnpm api
ui-ios-init:     preflight-rust preflight-node-pnpm preflight-ios
ui-ios-dev:      preflight-rust preflight-node-pnpm preflight-ios
ui-ios-build:    preflight-rust preflight-node-pnpm preflight-ios
api:             preflight-python
pad-build:       preflight-node-pnpm
test:            preflight-node-pnpm
slice:           preflight-node-pnpm
doctor:          preflight-node-pnpm
ui-local:        preflight-node-pnpm api
ui-preview:      preflight-node-pnpm pad-build
ui-lan:          preflight-node-pnpm preflight-python
ui-pwa:          preflight-node-pnpm preflight-python pad-build
install-cron:    preflight-launchctl
uninstall-cron:  preflight-launchctl
```

### `make doctor` is the comprehensive consumer

`scripts/doctor.mjs` calls `preflight.sh rust python node-pnpm` first, then layers project-specific checks (build artifacts, git remote, disk headroom, API port, pinned Tauri CLI version). Preflight stays fast and pure; doctor is the operator's "is everything healthy?" command.

## Examples

### ✓ Compliant — automata 2.20.0 (this PR)

Fresh-machine `make ui` with no Rust installed now prints:

```
┌─ automata preflight · missing toolchain ─────────────────┐
│  Tool        Rust (cargo + rustc)
│  Why needed  Tauri build · make ui · make ui-ios-*
│  Install:
│
│  bash scripts/stack/bootstrap-rust.sh        # native arm64 / arm64-linux / x86_64 (auto)
│
│  After install, open a new terminal or:
│      . "$HOME/.cargo/env"
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Run bootstrap_rust now? [y/N]
```

…and exits 1 before `pnpm tauri dev` ever fires.

### ✗ Violation — automata before 2.20.0 (2026-05-24 incident)

`make ui` on a fresh machine produced:

```
failed to run 'cargo metadata' command to get workspace directory:
failed to run command cargo metadata --no-deps --format-version 1:
No such file or directory (os error 2)
```

…with no hint that the fix is `curl https://sh.rustup.rs | sh`. The operator had to know to look for `cargo`, then know `rustup` is the install path, then know about Apple Silicon native vs Rosetta. This rule's existence is the prevention of the next re-discovery of that path.

### ✗ Violation — adding a target that shells out to `ffmpeg` without `preflight-ffmpeg`

```makefile
video-encode:
	@ffmpeg -i input.mov out.mp4   # no preflight — fresh machine sees "ffmpeg: command not found"
```

Compliant version:

```makefile
preflight-ffmpeg: ; @bash scripts/stack/preflight.sh ffmpeg
video-encode: preflight-ffmpeg
	@ffmpeg -i input.mov out.mp4
```

Plus a new `check_ffmpeg` + `hint_ffmpeg` block in `preflight.sh`.

## Why

Cryptic toolchain errors are a silent tax on every fresh-machine onboarding. They look like "the project is broken" instead of "you need to install $TOOL." The few seconds the operator spends seeing `cargo: command not found` is a fraction of the time spent then googling, finding rustup, debating brew-vs-curl, picking arm64-vs-x86_64, etc. — a 30-second decision becomes a 30-minute investigation.

Preflight + bootstrap turns that 30 minutes into 30 seconds: missing tool is named, the install command is one paste, the script is opt-in. Every future fresh-machine bootstrap of every operator app benefits forever after.

## Propagation

Per [`rule-propagation-discipline.md`](rule-propagation-discipline.md), this rule body lives in every operator-built repo's `.claude/rules/` + `.cursor/rules/` and the AI Skills Library. The IMPLEMENTATION (the actual `preflight.sh` + `bootstrap-*.sh` + Makefile wiring) lands in each repo's own PR when the rule is adopted there.

